06196nam a22008415i 9781442698376DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172012onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426983767 a10.3138/97814426983762doi  a(DE-B1597)483178  a(OCoLC)1004868247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR2976b.P67 2012eb 7aDRA0100002bisacsh04a822.3/322300aShakespeare and the Second World War :bMemory, Culture, Identity /ced. by Irena Makaryk, Marissa McHugh. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Theatre, War, Memory, and Culture -- t1 German Shakespeare, the Third Reich, and the War -- t2 Shakespearean Negotiations in the Perpetrator Society: German Productions of The Merchant of Venice during the Second World War -- t3 Shylock, Palestine, and the Second World War -- t4 ‘Caesar’s word against the world’: Caesarism and the Discourses of Empire -- t5 Shakespeare and Censorship during the Second World War: Othello in Occupied Greece -- t6 ‘In This Hour of History: Amidst These Tragic Events’ – Polish Shakespeare during the Second World War -- t7 Pasternak’s Shakespeare in Wartime Russia -- t8 Shakespeare as an Icon of the Enemy Culture in Wartime Japan, 1937–1945 -- t9 ‘Warlike Noises’: Jingoistic Hamlet during the Sino-Japanese Wars -- t10 Shakespeare, Stratford, and the Second World War -- t11 Rosalinds, Violas, and Other Sentimental Friendships: The Osiris Players and Shakespeare, 1939–1945 -- t12 Maurice Evans’s G.I. Hamlet: Analogy, Authority, and Adaptation -- t13 The War at ‘Home’: Representations of Canada and of the Second World War in Star Crossed -- t14 Shakespeare’s Merchant of Venice in Auschwitz -- t15 Appropriating Shakespeare in Defeat: Hamlet and the Contemporary Polish Vision of War -- tAppendix: List of Productions -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShakespeare’s works occupy a prismatic and complex position in world culture: they straddle both the high and the low, the national and the foreign, literature and theatre. The Second World War presents a fascinating case study of this phenomenon: most, if not all, of its combatants have laid claim to Shakespeare and have called upon his work to convey their society’s self-image.In wartime, such claims frequently brought to the fore a crisis of cultural identity and of competing ownership of this ‘universal’ author. Despite this, the role of Shakespeare during the Second World War has not yet been examined or documented in any depth. Shakespeare and the Second World War provides the first sustained international, collaborative incursion into this terrain. The essays demonstrate how the wide variety of ways in which Shakespeare has been recycled, reviewed, and reinterpreted from 1939–1945 are both illuminated by and continue to illuminate the War today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xLiterature and the war. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aDRAMA / Shakespeare.2bisacsh1 aAckermann, Zeno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarker, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayer, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBillingham, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourtney, Krystyna Kujawińska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgervari, Tibor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabicht, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula